text.text: A Guide to Bow

text.html: Spiritual home of all things cockney, Bow still has plenty of rhyming slang lurking round its streets, but now there's new blood coming in too. What does that mean? Proper salt of the earth establishments, along with some swish new additions, that's what. It's a mix that works well, me old china.

Proper salt of the earth establishments, along with some swish new additions, that's what. It's a mix that works well, me old china.
Best for... doing some good with your coffee

tip.text:
Talk about a feel-good coffee shop. You've got your homemade gluten-free and vegan cakes that are always top (they make an insanely good mascarpone icing here), and a range of Italian-style sandwiches that changes every day. There's also a sweet garden area out the back to chill out in.

One of the main draws here though is how much they care for the local community. You can leave money to buy a coffee for someone less fortunate as part of the Action Against Hunger campaign, and decorate a coffee that they'll display behind the counter, encouraging more people to donate.

Best for... getting back to nature

tip.text:
Just because there's a lot of inactive long-term residents here, doesn't mean there's not plenty going on all the time. This is one big nature reserve, filled with wildlife, and run by two separate charities who put on 120 free events a year, and 50 paid ones.

We're talking wild food walks, bat watching, even scything courses. Plus it's a genuinely tranquil place to get away from things when you just need to clear your noggin. It also hosts the Shuffle festival run by Danny Boyle every year. Look out for the resident celebrity cat roaming the grounds, Dr. P.

Best for... a proper (rude) East End experience

tip.text:
Fancy potentially getting yelled at and kicked out when trying to order a drink? The landlord and lady here are as old school East End as you can get, so you better not piss them off. Yep, The Palm Tree has a reputation for being a bit...unfriendly, but that's what people come for.

Inside it's dark as hell, lit by dim red lights, with photos of old celebrities you probably won't recognise. There's a small corner stage for live jazz - come on one of these nights and the vibe gets downright energetic.

Best for... all kinds of cultural goings on

tip.text:
Is it a cafe? Is it a music venue? Is it a gallery? There's so much going on here at this arts and culture space that it almost needs its own genre on the Dojo app.

Artisan breads and cakes made in-store by Breid, acoustic sets and chilled electronic music evenings, photography exhibitions, tapas, big breakfasts and pop up dinner events where you'll get Angolan and Brazilian grub? Muxima nails everything it tries.

Best for... a bit of everything

tip.text:
Hard to know where to start with this little funhouse of a pub - what got us first was the hidden room downstairs that's perfect for getting real messy in - the walls are two-way mirrors so you can see out but not in. There's a Smeg fridge inside you can fill up with booze too.

On the ground floor, live music on Thursday and Friday nights really kicks off, and on Sundays they specialise in Bloody Marys and Oysters. They do supper clubs upstairs too which can get pretty fancy.

Best for... a Sunday roast

tip.text:
Lots of pubs talk a big Sunday lunch game, but The Morgan Arms take roasts real seriously, but like real seriously. Just one look at the crunch on those potatoes will help you understand. If excellent pork belly isn't your thing, there's plenty of other top quality gastropub grub to be had - including restaurant quality food, breakfasts and burgers alike.

It's not a one trick pony though - the range of beers and ales get swapped out frequently so you can keep the old whistle drenched with the good stuff; and there's all sorts of organic and natural wines to be had too. On a warm evening you can sit out front with you pint, or play it cool with a negroni in the back garden.

text.text: Lots of pubs talk a big Sunday lunch game, but can they back it up? The Morgan Arms made it onto the Sunday Times' Top 20 Sunday Lunch list, and they're booked out 2 weeks in advance for it, so you know they roast up a mean bit of meat. It's not a one trick pony though - there's a private restaurant section in the back serving up a separate a la carte menu of contemporary British goodies. The range of beers and ales get swapped out frequently too, so you can keep the old whistle drenched with the good stuff.
Best for... some continental-style dining

tip.text:
There's a definite holiday vibe about Palmers - the bright interior, pale tiles and European menu make it feel like you could be any number of places abroad during the summer.

It's a bit like a few holidays rolled into one, because the menu spans a whole lot of borders. Harrisa Chicken Livers with Cous Cous bring the Mediterranean noise, while corn-fed chicken with black pudding and shallot pure bring the Brits to the table too. The wine list isn't massive, but you can't have everything.

Best for... getting snug

tip.text:
There's something about a coal fire in a pub, isn't there? Even better if there are two. Even better still if there are reclaimed church pews and lush red leather chairs to kick back in beside the fire while downing ale from the Dragonfly Brewery. And is that an old CD jukebox on the wall? 1 for 3 plays? Ok, this place is officially ticking all our boxes.

In the back is an open kitchen dining area where they whip up much slicker grub than normal pub standard - we had a brilliant cod loin when we were there, and saffron and butternut squash risotto. The mixture of old and new in here is nigh on perfect, and we love it.

Best... for pizza and pinball

tip.text:
We'll admit it...we first went into Lord Morpeth because we heard they had a working Pac Man machine as a table. Took us about a minute to see the 'Sourdough Saloon' menu on the table, so we got right on that like the greedy chancers we are. The pizzas they whip up are here are excellent: crisp bases, Rovagnati ham, fresh chilli, the best mozzarella...everything you need.

They throw in some good craft beers and a small cocktail list into the mix too. There's a pub quiz on Thursdays, live music some Fridays, and an open fire. Oh, and a jukebox and Star Wars pinball machine (we were obviously going to include those).
